The '''bank myna''' ('''''Acridotheres ginginianus''''') is a [[myna]] found in the northern parts of [[South Asia]]. It is smaller but similar in colouration to the [[common myna]], only differing in having brick-red naked skin behind the eyes instead of yellow. It is greyer on the underside and in this and in the presence of a slight tuft of feathers bears some resemblance to the [[jungle myna]]. They are found in flocks on the plains of northern and central India, often within towns and cities. Their range appears to be extending southwards into [[India]]. The name is derived from their habit of nesting almost exclusively in the earthen banks of rivers, where they excavate burrows and breed in large colonies.

==Description==
[[File:Bird India.jpg|thumb|Some of the wing feathers show green gloss|alt=|left]]

The head is black on the crown and sides and the upper plumage is slaty grey while the underside is lighter grey with pale pink plumage towards the centre of the abdomen. The wing is black but has a wing patch at the base of the primaries and the tips of the outer tail feathers are pale pinkish buff. The naked skin behind the eye is brick red, the legs are yellow while the iris is deep red. The sexes are indistinguishable in the field.<ref name="whistler">{{cite book |author=Whistler, Hugh |year=1949 |title=The Bank Myna |publisher=Gurney and Jackson, London |pages=205–206 |url=https://archive.org/stream/popularhandbooko033226mbp#page/n248/mode/1up |access-date=8 July 2013}}</ref> Young birds have a browner head and neck.<ref name="fbi2">{{cite book|pages=55–56|url=https://archive.org/stream/BakerFbiBirds3/BakerFBI3#page/n76/mode/1up/|title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds. Volume 3|edition=2nd|publisher=Taylor and Francis, London|author=Baker, E C S|year=1926}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/birdsindia01oaterich#page/538/mode/1up/| author= Oates, EW |year=1889|pages=538–539|title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds. Volume 1|publisher=Taylor and Francis, London}}</ref>

The species is evolutionarily closest to the [[common myna]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Zuccon, D. |author2=Pasquet, E. |author3=Ericson, P. G. P. |name-list-style=amp |year=2008 |title=Phylogenetic relationships among Palearctic–Oriental starlings and mynas (genera ''Sturnus'' and ''Acridotheres'': Sturnidae) |journal=Zoologica Scripta |volume=37 |issue=5 |pages=469–481 |url=https://www.nrm.se/download/18.251938811dab4a5dcc8000180/Zuccon%20et%20al%20Sturnus%20ZSC%202008.pdf |doi=10.1111/j.1463-6409.2008.00339.x |s2cid=56403448 |archive-date=2021-09-11 |access-date=2020-08-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210911171123/https://www.nrm.se/download/18.251938811dab4a5dcc8000180/Zuccon%20et%20al%20Sturnus%20ZSC%202008.pdf }}</ref>

==Habitat and distribution==
The native range of the bank myna is almost restricted to the Indian subcontinent from the Indus valley in the West to the Gangetic delta in the East and south of the lower foothills of the Himalayas, only rarely being found in sheltered valleys. They are found mainly in the vicinity of open water and their usual habitat is cultivated farmland and open country, but flocks will often live within cities, in markets and railway stations.<ref name="hbk" /> They make use of food scraps disposed by humans, even following catering vehicles at airports to standing aircraft.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ripley,S Dillon |year=1983| title=Habits of the Bank Myna ''Acridotheres ginginianus''.| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=80| issue=1| page=219|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48743809}}</ref>

[[File:Bank Mynas Im IMG 9770.jpg|thumb|left|Bank myna at Hodal, [[Haryana]], India]]

The distribution was formerly noted to be restricted north, roughly, of a line between Bombay and Balasore in Orissa, but the species may be expanding its range. They are also common in Pakistan in the districts of Sind and Punjab.{{citation needed|date=September 2020}} A specimen from Kandahar was earlier considered the westernmost record of a vagrant, but the birds have since established themselves in the region.<ref name="pcr">{{cite book|author1=Rasmussen PC  |author2=JC Anderton |name-list-style=amp |year=2005|title=Birds of South Asia. The Ripley Guide. Volume 2|publisher=Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions|page=584}}</ref> Although mainly resident, they make movements in response to food and weather.<ref name="hbk">{{cite book |last=Ali |first=Salim |author-link=Salim Ali |author2=Sidney Dillon Ripley |author2-link=Sidney Dillon Ripley |url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofbirdso0005alis/page/n5/mode/2up |title=Handbook of the Birds of India and Pakistan |edition=2nd |volume=5 |pages=181–182 |year=1986 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Choudhury,A |year=1997| title= New eastern limit of distribution of the Bank myna |journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=37| issue=2|pages=27–28|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW37_2#page/n8/mode/1up/}}</ref> The species name of the bird is based on the name given by Latham from a description by [[Pierre Sonnerat]] who described ''Le petit Martin de Gingi'' in 1782,<ref>{{cite book |author=Sonnerat, Pierre |year=1782|title=Voyage aux Indes Orientales et la Chine. Volume 2 |page=194 |url=http://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Voyage_aux_Indes_Orientales_et_%C3%A0_la_Chine_T2_page_194.jpg }}</ref> referring to [[Gingee]] near Pondicherry in southern India.<ref>{{cite book|year=1890|pages= 84–86|title=Catalogue of the birds in the British Museum. Volume 13 |url= https://archive.org/stream/catalogueofbirds13brit#page/83/mode/1up| author=Sharpe, R Bowdler| publisher= British Museum}}</ref> [[Thomas C. Jerdon]] noted in 1863 that the species did not occur in southern India however the species was recorded in the region in 1914 at Vandalur near Madras.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Raj,B Sundara |year=1914| title=The occurrence of the Bank Myna (''Acridotheres ginginianus'') near Madras| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume= 23| issue=1 |page=155|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30453510 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|pages=326–327| url=https://archive.org/stream/birdsofindiabein21jerd#page/326/mode/1up| author=Jerdon, TC|title= The birds of India. Volume 2. Part 1|year=1863| publisher=Military Orphan Press, Calcutta}}</ref> Records from further south in India are, however, increasing since 2000.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Khanna,L |year=1976| title= Bank Mynas ''Acridotheres ginginianus'' near Poona|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] | volume=16| issue=5| pages= 12–13| url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW16#page/n80/mode/1up}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB_5.5_153-154.pdf |title=Range extension of Bank Myna ''Acridotheres ginginianus'' in southern India with new records from Andhra Pradesh|author1=Taher, Humayun |author2=R. Sreekar |author3=Sivaji Anguru |author4=Siraj A. Taher  |name-list-style=amp |journal=Indian Birds|volume=5 | issue=5| year=2009 |pages=153–154}}</ref> Breeding colonies have been found in Assam.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Barooah, D |year=1993| title=Nesting colony of Bank Myna in Panidihing|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] | volume=33| issue=3|page=53| url= https://archive.org/stream/NLBW33_3#page/n14/mode/1up}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Jayakar, SD |author2=Werner, L |author3=Werner, Susan |year=1967| title= The arrival of the Bank Myna in Bhubaneshwar|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] | volume= 7| issue=3|page= 9| url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW7#page/n35/mode/1up}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author= Sankar,KJNG |year=1975| title= Occurrence of Bank Myna ''Acridotheres ginginianus'' (Latham) in Visakhapatnam (A.P.)|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=72|issue=3| pages=857–858 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48288049}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| author= Ambedkar, VC |year=1976| title= The Bank Myna (''Acridotheres ginginianus'') in Bombay|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=73|issue=1| page=217|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48293208 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Abdulali, Humayun |author2=Ali,Salim |year=1953| title=The Pied Myna and Bank Myna as birds of Bombay and Salsette| journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=51|issue=3|pages=736–737 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48202896}}</ref>

These mynas have been introduced into [[Kuwait]], where they have become established in the wild.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44784197 |title=The establishment of Bank Mynah Acridotheres ginginianus as a breeding species in Kuwait|author= Gregory, G. |author2=Al-Nasrallah, K.| journal=[[Sandgrouse (journal)|Sandgrouse]] |year=2001| volume=23| issue=2| pages=134–138 }}</ref> Flocks have also been found in the [[Maldives]], [[Taiwan]] and [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Occurrence, Distribution and Relative Abundance of Exotic Starlings and Mynas in Taiwan|author=Lin, Ruey-Shing |journal=特有生物研究 |volume=3|pages=13–23|year=2001|url=http://tesri.tesri.gov.tw/files/tesri_protect/47/013319485413_pdf.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002121004/http://tesri.tesri.gov.tw/files/tesri_protect/47/013319485413_pdf.pdf |archive-date=2 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Eguchi, Kazuhiro  |author2=Hitoha E. Amano |name-list-style=amp | year=2004|title= Invasive Birds in Japan|journal=Global Environment Research|volume=8|issue=1|pages=29–39|url=http://www.airies.or.jp/publication/ger/pdf/08-01-04.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303101534/http://www.airies.or.jp/publication/ger/pdf/08-01-04.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Forktail| volume =17| year=2001|pages= 67–73| title=New records of birds from the Maldives, with notes on other species|author1=Anderson, R C  |author2=M Baldock |name-list-style=amp |url=http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/17pdfs/Anderson-Maldives.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011235129/http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/17pdfs/Anderson-Maldives.pdf |archive-date=11 October 2008 }}</ref>

==Behaviour and ecology==
[[File:Bank Myna in Ajodhya Hills June 2025 by Tisha Mukherjee 02.jpg|thumb|Eating [[insect]] in [[Ajodhya Hills]], West Bengal, India.]]
Bank mynas are gregarious foraging in flocks, breeding colonially and roosting together in trees. They perch on livestock and live in crowded towns allowing close approach, often picking up scraps in markets and dumps.<ref name=hbk/> They are vociferous and use a wide range of calls that include clucks, croaks, screeches, whistles and warbling elements.<ref name=pcr/>

Bank mynas feed on grain, insects and fruits. Like the common myna, they sometimes follow grazing animals picking up disturbed insects or even ticks on the animals. They feed on ripening crops such as those of [[sorghum]], [[grape]] and [[pearl millet]]. They feed on a variety of insects, including some that are crop pests such as ''[[Achaea janata]]'' whose caterpillars feed on [[Castor oil plant|castor]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bhargava, RN |year=1981 |url=https://archive.org/details/NLBW21/page/n163/mode/2up | title=The Bank Myna ''Acridotheres ginginianus'' and King Crow ''Dicrurus adsimilis'' preying upon the Cricket ''Acheta'' (Orthopters: Gryllidae)|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=21| issue=12|pages=18–19}}</ref>

Bank mynas have a nesting season from April to July or August, most birds breeding in May and June. The nest is always built in earth walls, on the banks of rivers, embankments or the sides of open wells. They will sometimes make use of holes in brick walls. Nests have also been recorded between stacked bales of sugarcane stalks.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Lamba, BS |year=1981| title= A queer nesting site of Bank Myna, ''Acridotheres ginginianus''| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=78| issue=3| pages=605–606|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48229143}}</ref> They excavate the nest hole, the egg chamber sometimes 4 to 7 feet from the entrance. The nest is lined with grass, feathers and sometimes snake sloughs.<ref>{{cite book|pages=381–383|url=https://archive.org/stream/nestseggsofindia01hume#page/381/mode/1up|author=Hume, AO| title=The nests and eggs of Indian birds. Volume 1|publisher=R H Porter, London|year=1889|edition=2nd}}</ref> About four of five pale sky blue or greenish-blue eggs is the usual clutch.<ref name=whistler/> Two broods may be raised in the same season. The eggs hatch after about 13 to 14 days. Nestlings open their eyes after about 5 days and fledge in about 21 days. About 38% of the eggs hatched into young that fledged in one study.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Simwat, GS |author2=Sidhu, AS |year=1974| title= Developmental period and feeding habits of Bank Myna, ''Acridotheres ginginianus'' (latham) in Punjab| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=71|issue=2|pages=305–308|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48286504}}</ref>

A species of [[coccidia]]n parasite, ''Isospora ginginiana'', and several species of nematode (''Oxyspirura'', ''Choanotaenia'', ''Hymenolepis'' sp.) have been described from the species.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Chakravarty, M.  |author2=Kar, A.B.  |name-list-style=amp |year=1944| title= Studies on the coccidia of Indian birds. II. Observations on several species of coccidia of the sub-families Cyclosporinae and Eimeriinae|journal= Proceedings of the Indian Academy of Sciences, Section B |volume=20|issue=3 |pages=102–114|doi=10.1007/BF03049794 |url=https://archive.org/stream/proceedingsofthe020230mbp#page/n107/mode/1up}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=A Review of the Genus Oxyspirura Drasche in Stossich, 1897 (Nematoda: Thelaziidae) with Descriptions of Fourteen New Species |author1=Durdana S. Jairapuri  |author2=Ather H. Siddiqi |name-list-style=amp |journal=Journal of Helminthology|year=1967|volume=41|issue=4 |pages=337–363| doi= 10.1017/S0022149X00021891|pmid=6057047 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Studies On Cestodes of the Common Indian Mynahs Acridotheres Tristis and a. Ginginianus (Aves)|author=Saxena, S. Km.|journal= Netherlands Journal of Zoology| volume= 22| issue=3| year= 1971 |pages=307–334| doi=10.1163/002829672x00121}}</ref>
